  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why is it not possible for one to use 4 pairs of dry cells especially 12 volts to start a car when 12 volts of a wet cell can start a car?",
  "response": "Using dry cells to start a car is generally not feasible for several reasons despite both dry cells and wet cells providing 12 volts:\n\n1. **Current Capacity**:\n   - **Wet Cell (Lead-Acid Battery)**: These batteries can supply a high current (hundreds of amps) required to turn the starter motor of a car.\n   - **Dry Cell (e.g., Alkaline Battery)**: These batteries are typically designed to supply low current for smaller electronic devices. They cannot deliver the high surge current needed to start a car.\n\n2. **Internal Resistance**:\n   - **Wet Cell**: Has low internal resistance, allowing it to deliver high current without significant voltage drop.\n   - **Dry Cell**: Has higher internal resistance, which would cause significant voltage drop and prevent the sufficient current needed for the starter motor.\n\n3. **Capacity and Energy Density**:\n   - **Wet Cell**: Can store and deliver a lot of energy over a short period, ideal for starting an engine.\n   - **Dry Cell**: Usually has lower capacity and energy density, making them unsuitable for the high power demand of a car starter motor.\n\n4. **Design and Durability**:\n   - **Wet Cell**: Designed for automotive use, robust and durable to handle the vibrations and temperature variations of a car environment.\n   - **Dry Cell**: Not designed for such demanding applications, likely to fail under the physical stresses found in automotive use.\n\nIn summary, while both might be rated at 12 volts, the ability to deliver the required current and withstand the operational conditions makes a wet cell battery suitable for starting a car, while dry cells are not.",
